    88→/**
    89→ * Instances of RuleClass encapsulate the set of attributes of a given "class" of rule, such as
    90→ * <code>cc_binary</code>.
    91→ *
    92→ * <p>This is an instance of the "meta-class" pattern for Rules: we achieve using <i>values</i> what
    93→ * subclasses achieve using <i>types</i>. (The "Design Patterns" book doesn't include this pattern,
    94→ * so think of it as something like a cross between a Flyweight and a State pattern. Like Flyweight,
    95→ * we avoid repeatedly storing data that belongs to many instances. Like State, we delegate from
    96→ * Rule to RuleClass for the specific behavior of that rule (though unlike state, a Rule object
    97→ * never changes its RuleClass). This avoids the need to declare one Java class per class of Rule,
    98→ * yet achieves the same behavior.)
    99→ *
   100→ * <p>The use of a metaclass also allows us to compute a mapping from Attributes to small integers
   101→ * and share this between all rules of the same metaclass. This means we can save the attribute
   102→ * dictionary for each rule instance using an array, which is much more compact than a hashtable.
